<font color="#FF0000">WHY THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 18  5:56:18 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
I agree with John. I think that part of a US led Imperialist strategy involved expanding markets and eliminating opposition. The main opposition was communism. It is not that the capitalist leaders thought of Communism as evil, but rather it was a competitor in the market place. If you &quot;went Communist&quot; you were no longer a good place for a capital market or supplier of cheap resources. It is the same reason that they want those cheap Nike factories in S.E. Asia. It makes their profits higher than if they had to pay the going labor rate it the U.S. <br><br>
In the 60's there was a growing trend towards Communism and it was feared that if Vietnam went Communist, so would much of S.E.Asia. (The Domino Theory). So we decided to make a stand and try and prevent that trend from happening. Those same needs/desires were also evident throughout the Capitalist world. That is why other countries were in support and joined in our efforts.  <br><br>
This, with John's answer is some of what was involved. 
